*Construction*\line\line\b Base:\b0  Starting 16x16x16 Jorge airbrush.\line\b Map Size:\b0  Approximately 530x300x150 DromEd units. It takes about 70 seconds to run in a \lquote straight\rquote  line from the furthest south point to the furthest north point.\line\b Build Time:\b0  More than 53 days/1272 hours. I almost had the exact time, but on May 31\super st\nosupersub  the DromEd Info Window timer finally looped back and started the counter all over again. I think the time is kept as an unsigned 32-bit integer; my latest backup with the correct time says 48:14:26:50, and I definitely saw it at 49:16. Basically, I passed the DromEd kill-screen.\par
\i =============\par
\i0 +===+\line  \b IMPORTANT:\b0\line\emdash This FM comes with \lquote jump_speed_boost 1.4\rquote  enabled in fm.cfg, so it doesn\rquote t affect your settings for other Thief 2 FM/OMs. 1.4 is the Thief 1/Gold default, and this FM is intended to be played with Garrett\rquote s Thief 1/Gold movement. This FM \i can be completed\i0  using Thief 2\rquote s default 1.05 boost, but I \ul\i guarantee\ulnone\i0  this makes many non-essential jumps more difficult than they need to be (some are impossible at 1.05 unless you jump diagonally, and this is VERY annoying!). To disable this effect, put a semicolon (;) in front of the line in fm.cfg. I completely understand if don\rquote t want me dictating your controls.\line\emdash The intended ambient volume of this FM is 1100, which achieves my intended sfx to ambient volume ratio and avoids any line-level clipping. This command is disabled by default in the fm.cfg, however if you would like to hear the ambients at the volume I heard them at \i relative\i0  to footsteps and other sound effects, you can remove the ; in front of the \lquote ambient_volume 1100\rquote  command.\i\par
\i0\emdash I recommend you don\rquote t use any graphics mods to play this mission. My choice of textures and objects wasn\rquote t slapdash; many terrain brushes exist only to allow me more granular control over texture alignment and appearance.\par
+===+\line GAMEPLAY NOTES (MAY CONTAIN VERY LIGHT SPOILERS)\line\line    \emdash You are not missing any gameplay or content on lower difficulties. Expert has less equipment, but no less loot.\line    \emdash There are no invisible enemies.\line    \emdash There are no \lquote cryptic\rquote  clues in readables; if you can\rquote t pick up a readable, it isn\rquote t required to complete objectives. Most readables are shorter than one page.\line    \emdash No keys/loot are hidden under furniture or inside solid objects.\line    \emdash There are no micro-switches. Any hidden switches that may or may not exist would be normal size.\line    \emdash There are some \lquote challenging\rquote  jumps and mantling, but they are \i not\i0  necessary to complete objectives. Try jumping diagonally to cover more distance!\line    \emdash Some windows can be opened. If you have trouble getting through window frames, trying holding space and/or leaning though them.\line    \emdash\i Try mantling on everything\i0 ! Doors, signs, lights, trees, windows, walls, balconies, everything. Even torches, if you don\rquote t mind getting hot feet.\line    \emdash Wait until you reach the top of the rope arrow before jumping/mantling! (I \ul\i highly\ulnone\i0  recommend saving before using ropes in certain claustrophobic and smelly places\'85)\line    \emdash This missions \i cannot\i0  be Supreme or Strict Ghosted (some keys destroy on use, custom/scripted alert responses, maximum loot requires property damage etc.) However, if property damage is allowed, standard ghosting should be possible.\line    \emdash Given the non-linear elements of the level, I recommend marking where you\rquote ve explored on the map. Both exterior maps have variants with colour to differentiate heights and interiors/exteriors. These are included in the intrface/miss20 folder and, if you prefer them, just rename squarecolour.png as \i page001\i0 , and mainncolour.png as \i page002\i0 .\line\line +===+\line TECHNICAL NOTES\line  \line    \emdash This FM only supports FMSel, AngelLoader, or NewDarkLoader \emdash  these can load fm.cfg files.\line    \emdash This FM was made using NewDark 1.26. It might be compatible with an earlier 1.2x version, but I would recommend upgrading if only to play the dozens of excellent FMs that actually require 1.26. It runs with 1.23, but there might be some bug or incompatibility I didn\rquote t find.\line    \emdash This FM should not require a top-end PC. The frame-rate should scale with how powerful your computer is, and not be strangled by pushing NewDark beyond its technical limits. I ensured that the actual frame-rate \i NEVER\i0  dropped below 120fps, so 60fps should be easily achievable even for older systems.\par
+===+\line KNOWN ISSUES\line\line\emdash Pickpocket number is way off, at 14. Even after removing \lquote CulpableFor\rquote  link from arrows in quivers, the number is still off. If you don\rquote t count these arrows, it should be either 5 or 7, depending on what you consider a pickpocket.\par
+===+\line\line DISCLAIMER: This FM was designed under the assumption of mouse and keyboard usage. It should be fine to play with a gamepad, but if you struggle with any jumps/mantling, remember that analogue sticks aren\rquote t ideal for precise first-person movement, and that I didn\rquote t design this mission to be cruel or annoying. A lot of time and thought went into placing objects and brushes to optimise ease of mantling without sacrificing environmental or aesthetic immersion. In any case, quicksaving before a precarious decision is always prudent \emdash  who can predict the caprice of rope arrows?\par
